questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a critical order processing microservice is failing to roll back database changes during inventory shortfalls. Below is the simplified Spring Service implementation:

java
@Service
public class OrderProcessingService {
    @Autowired
    private OrderRepository orderRepository;

    @Transactional
    public void processOrder(Order order) {
        orderRepository.save(order);
        try {
            deductStock(order);
        } catch (InsufficientStockException e) {
            // Fallback: log and rethrow to trigger rollback
            throw e;
        }
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void deductStock(Order order) throws InsufficientStockException {
        // DB updates occur here
        if (order.getQuantity() > 100) {
            throw new InsufficientStockException("Out of stock!");
        }
    }
}


Despite `deductStock` throwing a checked `InsufficientStockException` and `processOrder` catching and rethrowing it, the outer transaction commits successfully, leaving the database in an inconsistent state.

You are debugging a production issue where a gRPC gateway microservice is experiencing severe thread-pool exhaustion and high memory usage under heavy load. The service aggregates downstream data using `CompletableFuture`. When a timeout or network failure occurs, the application attempts to cancel pending futures using the code below:

java
public CompletableFuture<List<Response>> aggregateData(List<Request> requests) {
    List<CompletableFuture<Response>> futures = requests.stream()
        .map(req -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> client.callBlocking(req), customExecutor))
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

    return CompletableFuture.allOf(futures.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0]))
        .thenApply(v -> futures.stream().map(CompletableFuture::join).collect(Collectors.toList()))
        .exceptionally(ex -> {
            futures.forEach(f -> f.cancel(true));
            return Collections.emptyList();
        });
}


During downstream latency spikes, active threads in `customExecutor` remain in a `BLOCKED` or `TIMED_WAITING` state indefinitely, eventually crashing the service with an `OutOfMemoryError` despite calling `cancel(true)`.
